“Well it’s a reasonable question,” you persisted.

I looked you in the eye. “The meaning of life, the reason I made this whole universe, is for you to mature.”

“You mean mankind? You want us to mature?”

“No, just you. I made this whole universe for you. With each new life you grow and mature and become a larger and greater intellect.”

“Just me? What about everyone else?”

“There is no one else,” I said. “In this universe, there’s just you and me.”

You stared blankly at me. “But all the people on earth…”

“All you. Different incarnations of you.”

“Wait. I’m everyone!?”

“Now you’re getting it,” I said, with a congratulatory slap on the back.

“I’m every human being who ever lived?”

“Or who will ever live, yes.”

“I’m Abraham Lincoln?”

“And you’re John Wilkes Booth, too,” I added.

“I’m Hitler?” You said, appalled.

“And you’re the millions he killed.”

“I’m Jesus?”

“And you’re everyone who followed him.”

You fell silent.

“Every time you victimized someone,” I said, “you were victimizing yourself. Every act of kindness you’ve done, you’ve done to yourself. Every happy and sad moment ever experienced by any human was, or will be, experienced by you.”

You thought for a long time.

“Why?” You asked me. “Why do all this?”

“Because someday, you will become like me. Because that’s what you are. You’re one of my kind. You’re my child.”

“Whoa,” you said, incredulous. “You mean I’m a god?”

“No. Not yet. You’re a fetus. You’re still growing. Once you’ve lived every human life throughout all time, you will have grown enough to be born.”

“So the whole universe,” you said, “it’s just…”

“An egg.” I answered. “Now it’s time for you to move on to your next life.”

And I sent you on your way.

>Is it true that there's a growing independence movement among Albertans?
Yes. One of the names that sentiment goes by is “Wexit.” Because of the nature of the Canadian political system and electoral structure, which is much closer to voting by population than the American system, the Canadian federal government is practically always selected by the major cities of Vancouver, Toronto, and Montreal. And those large cities growing in electoral power due to outrageous levels of mass migration being forced on us by the feds, because they know it perpetuates their hold on power.

>I know that Alberta is the only province of Canada that is a net payer into the Canadian government
Technically incorrect, but it might as well be correct in spirit. In general, Western Canada are all net contributors, but Alberta is the largest. It depends what year you’re looking at, or which average over which years, but Ontario is usually a net contributor. Quebec and Atlantic Canada are a pretty persistent net negative; in other words, they receive subsidies or tribute from the West in a bit of a quasi-colonial fashion.

Basically what’s going on is that, for a long time, Canada treated Quebec like shit, so they wanted to leave. After that came very close to happening, the feds started spoiling Quebec pretty hard with free shit, so now they’re not as eager to leave, but that free shit has to come from somewhere (i.e. Western Canada), so now after several decades of that, they’re pissed enough to want to leave instead.

There is a presumed right for Canadian provinces to secede, but the Quebec referenda have shown that the Canadian federal government is willing to play very dirty to make sure the votes go their way, with both the Sponsorship Scandal in the run-up as well as possible voter fraud, with people getting brought in by bus from out-of-province. The feds also passed a weird law, ironically called the Clarity Act, setting conditions for future secession referenda.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clarity_Act
One of the stipulations that has been left unclear is that it seems to demand a supermajority in favour of secession, rather than 50%+1, but then it doesn’t define what the actual necessary supermajority should be.

>Would it be accurate to describe Canada as a confederation as opposed to the U.S. which is a federation?
In general, I think so, yeah. It’s all spectral and there are aspects of federalism in Canada, but Canada does seem to be somewhat more decentralized than the United States in most areas of government.

ludzie nadal zamiast iść do lekarza, wziąć L4, wyleczyć się w domu chodzą chorzy po ulicy, do sklepu, pracy i zarażają innych.
Rozumiem, że czasem trzeba coś załatwić, zrobić zakupy czy coś. Ale wypada zachować jakieś środki ostrożności. Założyć maseczkę, kichać w zgięcie ręki itd. to tylko podstawy, niestety z obserwacji widzę, że dużo ludzi nic się nie nauczyło. Idę ulicą, ludzie prychają.
Stoję w sklepie w kolejce, ludzie kaszlą. W komunikacji miejskiej to samo. Widok maseczki to rzadkość, tak samo jak kichanie w zgięcie łokcia. Po co minimalizować rozprzestrzenie się wirusów, lepiej prychać na lewo i prawo, na innych ludzi.
W pracy to samo. Zakończenie roku to u mnie sajgon, gorący okres. Od wczoraj znajoma siedzi i kaszle przed siebie, na lewo, na prawo. Maseczki nie założy bo jej nie wygodnie, w łokieć nie kichnie, bo nie zdąży, do lekarza nie pójdzie, bo była w tym roku dwa razy na L4 i nie chce nadwyrężać, a pracy jest sporo. Więc sorry jej się nie chciało iść do lekarza, a przez to pół działu zaraz wyląduje na L4.

>>175625237
> /ie/ when stressed
Can I see the texbook?
This is technically true, but it's such an inconsequential phonetic detail. Teaching it to students is going to do more harm than good to their accents.
In simple terms, palatalization (or softness) is a [j]-like tongue gesture superimposed onto a consonant. Because there is a short lag before the transition to a vowel (due to physiological reasons), all Russian vowels following soft consonants have a barely noticeable palatal off-glide. In that sense, they can be considered diphthongs, because the vowel transitions from one point to another. [Cʲi̯e], [Cʲi̯æ], [Cʲi̯ɵ] for /Cʲe/, /Cʲa/, /Cʲa/ could be one way to transcribe this.
Notice how in the image, [i] and [e] start out with almost the same quality but then quickly diverge.
The problem is that this off-glide so short (probably around 10 ms) that it can only really be detected on a spectrogram. Non-phoneticians have no idea that it exists.
Any student that takes this advice will absolutely overdo it, and end up sounding stupid. A better idea would be to focus on getting palatalization down pat, which will automatically help you pronounce the vowel contours like a speaker would.
In general, due to the proliferation of palatalized and uvularized consonants, Russian vowels are very fluid and will transition towards two to three different points in the vowel space, depending on the sounds preceding and following them.
If you want to pronounce the vowels right, you need to learn the consonants first since they cause this in the first place.

To explain some of my corrections:
>İngilizce->İngilizceyi
When you're talking about general things like flowers or baseball, you don't add the -i suffix (becomes -(y)i with İngilizce since it ends with a vowel) indeed. You just say "Çiçek sever misin?" (not "seviyor musun," which is also correct but unnatural) indeed. But when talking about people or unique things like an entire language, you need the suffix.
>yeteneğini->becerilerin
"Yeteken" means talent. "Beceri" means skill. It's an important distinction.
Apart from that, "beceri-ler-in" is correct here, not "beceri-ler-in-i." The former just means "your skills," the latter is hard to describe but you'd use it in something like "Where did you learn your skills?" ("becerilerini nerede öğrendin?")

Too tired to explain the rest, peace.

>>175621010
They are indeed a lot less common. Personally, I've found that Germans (except Bavarians) barely use the term Mundart, whether in casual or formal speech. In Austria, we use both Mundart and Dialekt in casual speech, but I feel like younger generations tend more towards Dialekt.

I've never heard anyone say Verhältniswort and I have a linguistics background. Präposition is used almost exclusively. In general, there are three "tiers" of grammatical terms:
>Grundschule
Namenwort
Tunwort
Wiewort

>Mittelstufe
Hauptwort
Zeitwort
Eigenschaftswort

>Oberstufe and beyond
Nomen
Verb
Adjektiv

I would guess that Verhältniswort sounds a bit uneducated by analogy. Another reason why we tend to prefer the Latin term is probably because we only real start dealing with prepositions in a more in-depth way in Oberstufe.

Contrary to what most people will tell you prices don't simply go up, they are regulated by the market.
If it was possible to increase them anyone would have already done it, euro or not does not matter.
For example methane went absurdly high a few months ago because of the war and fears of scarcity, but now tanks are full and the weather is unusually mild and methane is for moment already back to its previous price.
If you increase any price more than the market can withstand you just go out of business, that's how really works.
The real problem isn't short term, it's long term. By adopting the euro you have lost the possibility to devalue your currency. If that happened a lot in the past, and the reasons why it has happened are still there, then you'll have problems in the long term.

Retningslinjer for opptreden ved personlig kontakt med den norske befolkning.

Enhver som tilhører Wehrmacht må være klar over at han ikke er i fiendeland, men at troppene rykker inn i Norge for å beskytte landet og sikre dets innbyggere. Derfor må man ta hensyn til følgende:

Nordmannen har en utpreget nasjonalbevissthet. Dessuten føler det norske folk seg meget nært beslektet med de øvrige nordiske folk. Altså: Unngå alt som kan såre den nasjonale æresfølelse!

Nordmannen er ytterst frihetselskende og selvbevisst. Han avviser enhver tvang og underkuelse. Han har ingen sans for militær tukt og autoritet. Altså: Gi minst mulig ordrer, ikke skrik til ham! Det fyller ham med trass og er uten virkning. Man oppnår mest med en spøkefull tone. Unødig skarphet og formynderskap sårer hans selvbevissthet.

Nordmannen er i sitt vesen (i likhet med den frisiske bonden) lukket og tilbakeholden, langsom i tanke og handlemåte, men dessuten også mistenksom overfor alt fremmed. Altså: Ikke noe hastverk! Bruk tid!

Nordmannens hjem er etter gammelgermansk oppfatning hellig. Han viser gjerne gjestfrihet. Eiendomsretten er ukrenkelig. Huset står ulåst. Tyveri er nesten ukjent og betraktes som en skam. Altså: Unngå ethvert uberettiget inngrep, selv om gjenstander ligger tilgjengelig rundt om. «Skafiing», «organisering» («orging») og lignende er det samme som tyveri, og er under enhver om-stendighet forbudt.

Nordmannen har ingen forståelse for krigen. Dette sjøfarende og handlende folk heller (mer) til England. Det frykter Russland. Med ubetydelige unntak finnes det ingen forståelse for nasjonal-sosialismens mål. Altså: Unngå politiske konfrontasjoner!

Nordmannen liker en hjemmekoselig, behagelig tilværelse. Han vinnes med vennlighet, med små oppmerksomheter og ved at man godtar hans person. Altså: Ingen påtrengenhet, særlig overfor kvinner!

Tysk språk forstås nesten overalt, hvis man snakker langsomt og tydelig.
